Introduction

This project examines whether changes in state-level employment influence the volume and success of crowdfunding activity in the United States. The central research question is:

Do stronger local labor markets lead to more entrepreneurial activity or higher success rates for crowdfunding projects?

The motivation is to understand whether stronger local labor markets, reflected in higher employment levels, support or hinder entrepreneurial activity on crowdfunding platforms. Higher employment may increase disposable income, local demand, and economic stability, which in turn may affect the ability of creators to launch and successfully fund projects.

Literature Review

Research on crowdfunding shows that entrepreneurial activity and funding outcomes on online platforms are shaped by geography, social networks, and local information frictions. Using data from an early online crowdfunding platform, Local and distant funders behave differently: nearby backers rely more on offline social ties and private information, while distant investors respond more to publicly observable funding dynamics and platform signals (Agrawal et al., 2015). Crowdfunding success is systematically related to project quality, founder characteristics, and geography, with regional clusters and local social capital associated with higher funding rates (Mollick, 2014). Together, these studies highlight that local context matters for crowdfunding outcomes, even in an online setting (Agrawal et al., 2015; Mollick, 2014).

A separate but related literature examines how local labor-market conditions affect entrepreneurship. Evidence from Germany shows that entrepreneurial entry is systematically related to the business cycle and local unemployment, with higher unemployment associated with more entry in some sectors (âunemployment pushâ) but also with weaker demand in others (âdemand pullâ) (Fritsch et al., 2015). More recent work develops a micro-founded model in which unemployed individuals are more likely to start firms, but those firms tend to be smaller and fail more often, implying that labor-market conditions shape both the quantity and quality of entrepreneurial activity (da Fonseca, 2022).

To estimate the causal effect of local labor-market strength on crowdfunding outcomes, this study uses a Bartik (shiftâshare) instrument constructed from pre-period stateâindustry employment shares and national industry employment shocks. Bartik-type instruments combine fixed local exposure weights with common shocks and can be interpreted as exposure-weighted averages of aggregate industry shocks (Breuer, 2022).

Data Description

Part 1: Kickstarter Excel Data

The dataset used in this project comes from the ICPSR 38050: Kickstarter Data, Global, 2009â2023 public-use archive. It contains over 610,000 Kickstarter projects launched worldwide, covering the platformâs major categories such as Film & Video, Games, Technology, Design, Art, and others. Each record includes structured project-level information such as category codes, subcategories, launch dates, deadlines, goal and pledged amounts, project currency, backer counts, country and state-level location identifiers, and project outcomes (successful, failed, canceled, suspended). ICPSR has masked certain identifying variables (e.g., project names and URLs) and excluded free-text blurbs to protect confidentiality. Location fields include standardized translations for non-Latin text, and monetary values are provided in both original currency and USD. This dataset allows detailed analysis of global crowdfunding patterns across time, geography, and creative domains.

1-1: Projects per Year by Region (Non-US, US, Total)

Code 
df_ks$LAUNCHED_DATE <- suppressWarnings(as.Date(df_ks$LAUNCHED_DATE, format = "%m/%d/%y"))

# Create YEAR variable
df_ks$YEAR <- as.integer(format(df_ks$LAUNCHED_DATE, "%Y"))

# Create US vs Non-US classification
state_map <- setNames(state.name, state.abb)
df_ks$US_STATE <- state_map[df_ks$PROJECT_PAGE_LOCATION_STATE]
df_ks$IS_US <- ifelse(!is.na(df_ks$US_STATE), "US", "Non-US")

year_summary <- df_ks %>%
  filter(!is.na(YEAR)) %>%
  group_by(YEAR, IS_US) %>%
  summarize(Count = n(), .groups = "drop") %>%
  tidyr::pivot_wider(
    names_from = IS_US,
    values_from = Count,
    values_fill = 0
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    Total = US + `Non-US`,
    YEAR = as.character(YEAR)
  ) %>%
  arrange(YEAR)

total_row <- tibble(
  YEAR = "Total",
  `Non-US` = sum(year_summary$`Non-US`, na.rm = TRUE),
  US = sum(year_summary$US, na.rm = TRUE),
  Total = sum(year_summary$Total, na.rm = TRUE)
)

year_summary_final <- bind_rows(year_summary, total_row)

# TABLE
kable(year_summary_final,
      caption = "Projects per Year (Non-US, US, Total)") %>%
  kable_styling(full_width = FALSE) %>%
  row_spec(nrow(year_summary_final), bold = TRUE)

# Prepare for line chart (same style as 1-2)
year_long <- year_summary %>%
  select(YEAR, `Non-US`, US, Total) %>%
  tidyr::pivot_longer(
    cols = c(`Non-US`, US, Total),
    names_to = "Region",
    values_to = "Count"
  )

# LINE CHART (same style as 1-2)
ggplot(year_long, aes(x = YEAR, y = Count, color = Region, group = Region)) +
  geom_line(size = 1.2) +
  geom_point(size = 2) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c(
    "Non-US" = "red",
    "US" = "blue",
    "Total" = "gray40"
  )) +
  labs(
    title = "Projects per Year by Region (Non-US, US, Total)",
    x = "Year",
    y = "Number of Projects"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

1-2: Success Rates by Year (US vs Non-US)

Code 
df_ks$success_flag <- ifelse(df_ks$STATE == "successful", 1, 0)

temp <- df_ks %>%
  group_by(YEAR, IS_US) %>%
  summarize(
    total = n(),
    successful = sum(success_flag),
    .groups = "drop"
  )

success_year <- temp %>%
  tidyr::pivot_wider(
    names_from = IS_US,
    values_from = c(total, successful),
    names_glue = "{.value}_{IS_US}",
    values_fill = 0
  )

if (!"total_US" %in% names(success_year)) success_year$total_US <- 0
if (!"total_Non-US" %in% names(success_year)) success_year$`total_Non-US` <- 0
if (!"successful_US" %in% names(success_year)) success_year$successful_US <- 0
if (!"successful_Non-US" %in% names(success_year)) success_year$`successful_Non-US` <- 0

success_year <- success_year %>%
  mutate(
    YEAR = as.character(YEAR),
    `Non-US` = `total_Non-US`,
    US = total_US,
    Total = `Non-US` + US,
    `Success Rate Non-US` = ifelse(`Non-US` > 0, `successful_Non-US` / `Non-US`, NA),
    `Success Rate US` = ifelse(US > 0, successful_US / US, NA),
    `Success Rate Total` = (successful_US + `successful_Non-US`) / Total
  ) %>%
  select(
    YEAR,
    `Non-US`, US, Total,
    `Success Rate Non-US`,
    `Success Rate US`,
    `Success Rate Total`
  ) %>%
  arrange(YEAR)

total_row <- tibble(
  YEAR = "Total",
  `Non-US` = sum(success_year$`Non-US`),
  US = sum(success_year$US),
  Total = sum(success_year$Total),
  `Success Rate Non-US` =
      sum(success_year$`Success Rate Non-US` * success_year$`Non-US`) /
      sum(success_year$`Non-US`),
  `Success Rate US` =
      sum(success_year$`Success Rate US` * success_year$US) /
      sum(success_year$US),
  `Success Rate Total` =
      sum(success_year$`Success Rate Total` * success_year$Total) /
      sum(success_year$Total)
)

# Combine
success_year_final <- bind_rows(success_year, total_row)

kable(success_year_final,
      digits = 3,
      caption = "Success Rates by Year (Non-US, US, Total)") %>%
  kable_styling(full_width = FALSE) %>%
  row_spec(nrow(success_year_final), bold = TRUE)

success_long <- success_year %>%
  select(
    YEAR,
    `Success Rate Non-US`,
    `Success Rate US`,
    `Success Rate Total`
  ) %>%
  pivot_longer(
    cols = starts_with("Success Rate"),
    names_to = "Region",
    values_to = "Rate"
  )

# Plot
ggplot(success_long, aes(x = YEAR, y = Rate, color = Region, group = Region)) +
  geom_line(size = 1.2) +
  geom_point(size = 2) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c(
    "Success Rate Non-US" = "red",
    "Success Rate US" = "blue",
    "Success Rate Total" = "gray40"
  )) +
  labs(
    title = "Success Rates by Year (Non-US, US, Total)",
    x = "Year",
    y = "Success Rate"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

state_map <- setNames(state.name, state.abb)

    Total = n(),

Part 2: U.S. Employment Data (BLS CES)

This section introduces the second major dataset used in the project: U.S. stateâindustry employment from the BLS Current Employment Statistics (CES) program. The CES dataset provides monthly employment counts for all states and major industries between 2010 and 2024. These data allow us to construct stateâyear employment totals and compute baseline industry shares.

2-1: Introduction to the Employment Dataset

The dataset includes:

  • Monthly employment levels for each state Ã industry
  • State and industry identifiers
  • Coverage of nine major CES super-sectors

These data allow us to quantify differences in labor-market size, industry composition, and year-to-year fluctuations across states. Combined with the Kickstarter dataset, this enables analysis of whether regions experiencing stronger labor-market growth tend to have higher crowdfunding activity or success rates.

2-2: Load and Clean the Employment Data

Code 
library(stringr)

# Load file
df <- read_excel("bls_employment_state_2010_2024.xlsx")

month_cols <- grep("^[A-Za-z]{3}[0-9]{4}$", names(df), value = TRUE)

df_long <- df %>%
  pivot_longer(
    cols = all_of(month_cols),
    names_to = "month_year",
    values_to = "value"
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    Year = as.numeric(str_sub(month_year, -4, -1))
  )

df_yearly <- df_long %>%
  group_by(state_name, industry, Year) %>%
  summarize(value = mean(value, na.rm = TRUE), .groups = "drop")

table_out <- df_yearly %>%
  pivot_wider(
    names_from = Year,
    values_from = value
  ) %>%
  arrange(state_name, industry)


table_out %>%
  mutate(across(where(is.numeric), ~round(., 1))) %>%
  kbl(
    caption = "Yearly Average Employment by State and Industry (2010â2024)",
    align = "lcccccccccccccc",
    booktabs = TRUE,
    format = "html"
  ) %>%
  kable_styling(
    bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover", "condensed"),
    full_width = FALSE,
    font_size = 12
  ) %>%
  scroll_box(height = "500px")

Empirical Strategy

The empirical analysis links stateâyear Kickstarter outcomes to local labor-market conditions, using a Bartik (shiftâshare) instrument for state-level employment.

Let:

  • \(s\) index states and \(t\) index years
  • \(\text{Emp}_{s,t} = \log(\text{total state employment in thousands})\), constructed from CES data
  • \(\text{CF}_{s,t}\) denote a Kickstarter outcome (here, the success rate of projects in state \(s\), year \(t\).
  • \(\eta_s\) and \(\tau_t\) denote state and year fixed effects

Stage 1: Employment and the Bartik Instrument

The first stage relates log employment to a Bartik (shiftâshare) instrument:

\[ \text{Emp}_{s,t} = \alpha + \lambda B_{s,t} + \eta_s + \tau_t + \varepsilon_{s,t}, \]

where \(B_{s,t}\) is the Bartik term defined as:

\[ B_{s,t} = \sum_k \text{share}^{\text{base}}_{s,k} \cdot g_{k,t}. \]

Here:

  • \(\text{share}^{\text{base}}_{s,k}\) is the baseline employment share of industry \(k\) in state \(s\), computed from average stateâindustry employment over 2010â2012. These shares are fixed over time.
  • \(g_{k,t} = \Delta \log(\text{national employment in industry } k)\) is the national industry shock, measured as the year-on-year log change in total U.S. employment in industry \(k\).

Because the exposure shares \(\text{share}^{\text{base}}_{s,k}\) are state-specific but time-invariant, and the shocks \(g_{k,t}\) are common across states but time-varying, the product \(\text{share}^{\text{base}}_{s,k} \cdot g_{k,t}\) generates differential predicted employment shocks across states. With state and year fixed effects, the variation in \(B_{s,t}\) comes from differences in industrial composition interacting with aggregate industry trends, providing plausibly exogenous shifts in local employment.

Stage 2: Crowdfunding Outcomes

The second stage uses the predicted log employment from the first stage to estimate its effect on Kickstarter performance:

\[ \text{CF}_{s,t} = \beta\,\widehat{\text{Emp}}_{s,t} + \gamma \log(\text{total\_projects}_{s,t}) + \eta_s + \tau_t + u_{s,t}, \]

where:

  • \(\widehat{\text{Emp}}_{s,t}\) is the fitted value of log employment from the first-stage regression.
  • \(\log(\text{total\_projects}_{s,t})\) controls for the scale of Kickstarter activity in each stateâyear cell.
  • \(\eta_s\) and \(\tau_t\) again capture time-invariant state factors and common year shocks.

In practice, these equations are estimated using two-stage least squares with fixed effects via the fixest package. The OLS specification regresses \(\text{CF}_{s,t}\) directly on \(\text{Emp}_{s,t}\), whereas the IV specification instruments \(\text{Emp}_{s,t}\) with \(B_{s,t}\). The coefficient \(\beta\) is interpreted as the causal effect of log state employment levels on the crowdfunding success rate, under the usual Bartik assumptions of instrument relevance and exogeneity (national industry shocks, interacted with pre-period shares, affect crowdfunding outcomes only through their impact on local employment).

In what follows, I implement this framework in four steps:

  1. Construct a stateâyear panel of Kickstarter activity (total projects and success rates).
  2. Aggregate CES employment to stateâyear totals and build baseline industry shares.
  3. Construct the Bartik instrument from national industry shocks and baseline shares.
  4. Merge the datasets and estimate OLS and IV models at the stateâyear level.
  • StateâYear Kickstarter Panel (U.S. Only)

The first step in implementing the empirical strategy is to construct a stateâyear panel of Kickstarter activity for U.S. states. Using the cleaned Kickstarter dataset, I aggregate all projects within each stateâyear cell to obtain three key measures:

  • total_projects: the number of projects launched in state \(s\) during year \(t\)
  • successful_projects: the number of those projects that reached or exceeded their funding goal
  • success_rate: the share of projects that were successful,
    \[ \mathrm{success\_rate}_{s,t} = \frac{\mathrm{successful\_projects}_{s,t}} {\mathrm{total\_projects}_{s,t}}. \]

To ensure that the panel captures state-level economic environments that are comparable to the employment data, I restrict attention to U.S.-based projects only, identified using standardized state codes mapped to full state names. I also retain only observations with valid launch dates, allowing consistent computation of the calendar year of project initiation.

The resulting dataset is a balanced summary of Kickstarter activity across all U.S. states and years in which projects were observed, and it forms the outcome panel that will later be merged with stateâyear employment totals and the Bartik instrument.

Code 
ks_us_state_year <- df_ks %>%
  filter(
    IS_US == "US",
    !is.na(STATE_NAME),
    !is.na(YEAR)
  ) %>%
  group_by(STATE_NAME, YEAR) %>%
  summarize(
    total_projects = n(),
    successful_projects = sum(success_flag, na.rm = TRUE),
    success_rate = successful_projects / total_projects,
    .groups = "drop"
  )

ks_us_state_year %>%
  arrange(STATE_NAME, YEAR) %>%
  head(20) %>%
  kbl(
    digits = 3,
    caption = "Sample of U.S. StateâYear Kickstarter Panel"
  ) %>%
  kable_styling(full_width = FALSE)

Results

To link Kickstarter outcomes to local economic conditions, I construct stateâyear measures of total employment using the CES dataset. For each stateâindustry pair, the CES data provide monthly employment levels, which I average to obtain annual employment. Summing across industries within each stateâyear gives a measure of the overall size of the labor market:

\[ \text{emp\_total}_{s,t} = \sum_k \text{employment}_{s,k,t}, \qquad \text{Emp}_{s,t} = \log(\text{emp\_total}_{s,t}). \]

These log employment levels form the endogenous variable in the instrumental variables strategy.

A key ingredient of the Bartik instrument is a set of fixed exposure weights, capturing the long-run industrial composition of each state. I compute these weights using average employment shares from the pre-period 2010â2012:

\[ \text{share}^{\text{base}}_{s,k} = \frac{\overline{\text{employment}}_{s,k,2010â2012}} {\sum_j \overline{\text{employment}}_{s,j,2010â2012}}. \]

These baseline shares vary across states but are constant over time. They reflect each stateâs historical specialization across industries and are used to scale national industry shocks when constructing the Bartik instrument in the next subsection.

To validate these weights, I check that shares sum to one within each state and that all states have complete industry coverage. The resulting dataset provides both (i) annual total employment by state and (ii) fixed state, industry exposure weights, both of which are necessary for building the shiftâshare instrument.

Code 
state_emp <- df_yearly %>%
  group_by(state_name, Year) %>%
  summarize(
    emp_total = sum(value, na.rm = TRUE),
    .groups = "drop"
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    log_emp_total = log(emp_total)
  )

# Baseline industry shares using early years (2010â2012)
baseline_shares <- df_yearly %>%

  ) %>%

1: National Industry Shocks and Bartik Instrument

The Bartik instrument combines fixed stateâindustry exposure weights with national industry employment shocks. Using the CES data, I first compute national employment for each industry and year and construct annual macroeconomic shocks as year-on-year log changes:

\[ g_{k,t} = \Delta \log(\text{national employment in industry } k). \]

These shocks capture national demand or technological trends that shift employment in each industry in ways unrelated to individual states.

The Bartik instrument for state \(s\) in year \(t\) is then constructed as a weighted average of these shocks, using the fixed baseline stateâindustry shares from 2010â2012:

\[ B_{s,t} = \sum_k \text{share}^{\text{base}}_{s,k} \cdot g_{k,t}. \]

Because the exposure shares vary across states but are fixed over time, and the national shocks vary across years but are common across states, their interaction generates state-specific predicted changes in employment driven only by national industry trends. This provides plausibly exogenous variation for identifying the causal effect of local employment on Kickstarter outcomes.

The resulting stateâyear series \(B_{s,t}\) excludes the first year of data, as national shocks require lagged employment to compute year-over-year changes.

Code 
# National industry employment and shocks
nat_industry <- df_yearly %>%
  group_by(industry, Year) %>%
  summarize(
    emp_nat = sum(value, na.rm = TRUE),
    .groups = "drop"
  ) %>%
  arrange(industry, Year) %>%
  group_by(industry) %>%
  mutate(
    g_shock = log(emp_nat) - log(lag(emp_nat))   # Î log national employment
  ) %>%
  ungroup()

# Stateâyear Bartik instrument: sum_k share_{s,k} * g_shock_{k,t}
bartik_panel <- baseline_shares %>%
  select(state_name, industry, share) %>%
  left_join(nat_industry, by = "industry") %>%
  group_by(state_name, Year) %>%
  summarize(
    bartik_iv = sum(share * g_shock, na.rm = TRUE),
    .groups = "drop"
  ) %>%
  filter(!is.na(bartik_iv))   # drop first year with missing shocks

# Quick check
bartik_panel %>%
  arrange(state_name, Year) %>%
  head(20) %>%
  kbl(
    digits = 4,
    caption = "Sample of Bartik Instrument by State and Year"
  ) %>%
  kable_styling(full_width = FALSE)

3: OLS and Instrumental Variables Estimates

In the final step, I estimate the relationship between stateâyear Kickstarter performance and local labor-market conditions. The outcome variable is the success rate of projects launched in each stateâyear cell. The key regressor is the log of total state employment, which is potentially endogenous due to omitted economic conditions that may jointly influence employment and crowdfunding activity.

I first estimate a fixed-effects OLS model of the form:

\[ \text{success\_rate}_{s,t} = \beta_{\text{OLS}}\;\text{Emp}_{s,t} + \gamma\,\log(\text{projects}_{s,t}) + \eta_s + \tau_t + \varepsilon_{s,t}, \]

where \(\eta_s\) and \(\tau_t\) capture all time-invariant state characteristics and nationwide year shocks.

To address the endogeneity of employment, I then use the Bartik instrument constructed earlier to obtain a consistent 2SLS estimate:

\[ \text{success\_rate}_{s,t} = \beta_{\text{IV}}\;\widehat{\text{Emp}}_{s,t} + \gamma\,\log(\text{projects}_{s,t}) + \eta_s + \tau_t + u_{s,t}, \]

with the first stage:

\[ \text{Emp}_{s,t} = \lambda B_{s,t} + \eta_s + \tau_t + \nu_{s,t}. \]

The IV specification therefore identifies the effect of predicted employment growth driven by national industry trends interacting with fixed state-level industry composition. The coefficient \(\beta_{\text{IV}}\) represents the causal effect of employment on crowdfunding success under the exclusion restriction.

Code 
library(fixest)
library(modelsummary)

# OLS with state and year fixed effects
ols_model <- feols(
  success_rate ~ log_emp_total + log_total_projects | STATE_NAME + YEAR,
  data = panel
)

# IV model: log_emp_total instrumented by bartik
iv_model <- feols(
  success_rate ~ log_total_projects | STATE_NAME + YEAR |
    log_emp_total ~ bartik_iv,
  data = panel
)

# Compare results
modelsummary(
  list(
    "OLS"        = ols_model,
    "IV (BARTIK)" = iv_model
  ),
  coef_map = c(
    "log_emp_total"      = "Log Employment",
    "log_total_projects" = "Log Total Projects",
    "fit_log_emp_total"  = "Fitted Log Employment"
  ),
  stars = TRUE,
  statistic = "({std.error})",
  gof_omit = "AIC|BIC|Log.Lik|F|RMSE|Std.Errors"
)

Conclusion

The OLS results show no evidence of a relationship between log employment and Kickstarter success rates at the stateâyear level. The estimated coefficient is close to zero (0.007) and statistically insignificant. This suggests that, in simple fixed-effects regressions, variation in state employment levels does not meaningfully predict crowdfunding success after accounting for differences in project volume and unobserved state and year effects.

The IV estimates using the Bartik shiftâshare instrument also produce an imprecise coefficient on log employment. The point estimate is larger (0.212) but remains far from statistically significant, and the associated standard error is substantial (0.648). This pattern indicates a weak first stage: the Bartik instrument does not strongly predict state-level employment within this sample, making it challenging to obtain a precise causal estimate.

## Introduction

This project examines whether changes in state-level employment influence the volume and success of crowdfunding activity in the United States. The central research question is:

*Do stronger local labor markets lead to more entrepreneurial activity or higher success rates for crowdfunding projects?*

The motivation is to understand whether stronger local labor markets, reflected in higher employment levels, support or hinder entrepreneurial activity on crowdfunding platforms. Higher employment may increase disposable income, local demand, and economic stability, which in turn may affect the ability of creators to launch and successfully fund projects.

## Literature Review

Research on crowdfunding shows that entrepreneurial activity and funding outcomes on online platforms are shaped by geography, social networks, and local information frictions. Using data from an early online crowdfunding platform, Local and distant funders behave differently: nearby backers rely more on offline social ties and private information, while distant investors respond more to publicly observable funding dynamics and platform signals ([Agrawal et al., 2015](#agrawal2015)). Crowdfunding success is systematically related to project quality, founder characteristics, and geography, with regional clusters and local social capital associated with higher funding rates ([Mollick, 2014](#mollick2014)). Together, these studies highlight that local context matters for crowdfunding outcomes, even in an online setting ([Agrawal et al., 2015](#agrawal2015); [Mollick, 2014](#mollick2014)).

A separate but related literature examines how local labor-market conditions affect entrepreneurship. Evidence from Germany shows that entrepreneurial entry is systematically related to the business cycle and local unemployment, with higher unemployment associated with more entry in some sectors (âunemployment pushâ) but also with weaker demand in others (âdemand pullâ) ([Fritsch et al., 2015](#fritsch2015)). More recent work develops a micro-founded model in which unemployed individuals are more likely to start firms, but those firms tend to be smaller and fail more often, implying that labor-market conditions shape both the quantity and quality of entrepreneurial activity ([da Fonseca, 2022](#dafonseca2022)).

To estimate the causal effect of local labor-market strength on crowdfunding outcomes, this study uses a Bartik (shiftâshare) instrument constructed from pre-period stateâindustry employment shares and national industry employment shocks. Bartik-type instruments combine fixed local exposure weights with common shocks and can be interpreted as exposure-weighted averages of aggregate industry shocks ([Breuer, 2022](#breuer2022)).

## Data Description

### Part 1: Kickstarter Excel Data

The dataset used in this project comes from the ICPSR 38050: Kickstarter Data, Global, 2009â2023 public-use archive. It contains over 610,000 Kickstarter projects launched worldwide, covering the platformâs major categories such as Film & Video, Games, Technology, Design, Art, and others. Each record includes structured project-level information such as category codes, subcategories, launch dates, deadlines, goal and pledged amounts, project currency, backer counts, country and state-level location identifiers, and project outcomes (successful, failed, canceled, suspended). ICPSR has masked certain identifying variables (e.g., project names and URLs) and excluded free-text blurbs to protect confidentiality. Location fields include standardized translations for non-Latin text, and monetary values are provided in both original currency and USD. This dataset allows detailed analysis of global crowdfunding patterns across time, geography, and creative domains.

### Part 2: U.S. Employment Data (BLS CES)

This section introduces the second major dataset used in the project: U.S. stateâindustry employment from the BLS Current Employment Statistics (CES) program. The CES dataset provides monthly employment counts for all states and major industries between 2010 and 2024. These data allow us to construct stateâyear employment totals and compute baseline industry shares.

#### 2-1: Introduction to the Employment Dataset

The dataset includes:

* Monthly employment levels for each state Ã industry
* State and industry identifiers
* Coverage of nine major CES super-sectors

These data allow us to quantify differences in labor-market size, industry composition, and year-to-year fluctuations across states. Combined with the Kickstarter dataset, this enables analysis of whether regions experiencing stronger labor-market growth tend to have higher crowdfunding activity or success rates.

#### 2-2: Load and Clean the Employment Data

```{r load-employment}
library(stringr)

df <- read_excel("bls_employment_state_2010_2024.xlsx")
```

## Empirical Strategy

The empirical analysis links stateâyear Kickstarter outcomes to local labor-market conditions, using a Bartik (shiftâshare) instrument for state-level employment.

Let:

- $s$ index states and $t$ index years  
- $\text{Emp}_{s,t} = \log(\text{total state employment in thousands})$, constructed from CES data  
- $\text{CF}_{s,t}$ denote a Kickstarter outcome (here, the **success rate** of projects in state $s$, year $t$.
- $\eta_s$ and $\tau_t$ denote **state** and **year fixed effects**

#### Stage 1: Employment and the Bartik Instrument

The first stage relates log employment to a Bartik (shiftâshare) instrument:

$$
\text{Emp}_{s,t} = \alpha + \lambda B_{s,t} + \eta_s + \tau_t + \varepsilon_{s,t},
$$

where $B_{s,t}$ is the Bartik term defined as:

$$
B_{s,t} = \sum_k \text{share}^{\text{base}}_{s,k} \cdot g_{k,t}.
$$

Here:

- $\text{share}^{\text{base}}_{s,k}$ is the **baseline employment share** of industry $k$ in state $s$, computed from average stateâindustry employment over 2010â2012. These shares are fixed over time.
- $g_{k,t} = \Delta \log(\text{national employment in industry } k)$ is the **national industry shock**, measured as the year-on-year log change in total U.S. employment in industry $k$.

Because the exposure shares $\text{share}^{\text{base}}_{s,k}$ are state-specific but time-invariant, and the shocks $g_{k,t}$ are common across states but time-varying, the product $\text{share}^{\text{base}}_{s,k} \cdot g_{k,t}$ generates differential predicted employment shocks across states. With state and year fixed effects, the variation in $B_{s,t}$ comes from differences in industrial composition interacting with aggregate industry trends, providing plausibly exogenous shifts in local employment.

#### Stage 2: Crowdfunding Outcomes

The second stage uses the predicted log employment from the first stage to estimate its effect on Kickstarter performance:

$$
\text{CF}_{s,t} = \beta\,\widehat{\text{Emp}}_{s,t}
                 + \gamma \log(\text{total\_projects}_{s,t})
                 + \eta_s + \tau_t + u_{s,t},
$$

where:

- $\widehat{\text{Emp}}_{s,t}$ is the **fitted value of log employment** from the first-stage regression.
- $\log(\text{total\_projects}_{s,t})$ controls for the scale of Kickstarter activity in each stateâyear cell.
- $\eta_s$ and $\tau_t$ again capture time-invariant state factors and common year shocks.

In practice, these equations are estimated using two-stage least squares with fixed effects via the `fixest` package. The OLS specification regresses $\text{CF}_{s,t}$ directly on $\text{Emp}_{s,t}$, whereas the IV specification instruments $\text{Emp}_{s,t}$ with $B_{s,t}$. The coefficient $\beta$ is interpreted as the **causal effect of log state employment levels on the crowdfunding success rate**, under the usual Bartik assumptions of instrument relevance and exogeneity (national industry shocks, interacted with pre-period shares, affect crowdfunding outcomes only through their impact on local employment).

In what follows, I implement this framework in four steps:

1. Construct a stateâyear panel of Kickstarter activity (total projects and success rates).  
2. Aggregate CES employment to stateâyear totals and build baseline industry shares.  
3. Construct the Bartik instrument from national industry shocks and baseline shares.  
4. Merge the datasets and estimate OLS and IV models at the stateâyear level.

---

- StateâYear Kickstarter Panel (U.S. Only)

The first step in implementing the empirical strategy is to construct a stateâyear panel of Kickstarter activity for U.S. states. Using the cleaned Kickstarter dataset, I aggregate all projects within each stateâyear cell to obtain three key measures:

- **total_projects**: the number of projects launched in state $s$ during year $t$  
- **successful_projects**: the number of those projects that reached or exceeded their funding goal  
- **success_rate**: the share of projects that were successful,  
$$
\mathrm{success\_rate}_{s,t} =
\frac{\mathrm{successful\_projects}_{s,t}}
     {\mathrm{total\_projects}_{s,t}}.
$$


To ensure that the panel captures state-level economic environments that are comparable to the employment data, I restrict attention to U.S.-based projects only, identified using standardized state codes mapped to full state names. I also retain only observations with valid launch dates, allowing consistent computation of the calendar year of project initiation.

The resulting dataset is a balanced summary of Kickstarter activity across all U.S. states and years in which projects were observed, and it forms the outcome panel that will later be merged with stateâyear employment totals and the Bartik instrument.


```{r ks-state-year}

ks_us_state_year <- df_ks %>%
  filter(
    IS_US == "US",
    !is.na(STATE_NAME),
    !is.na(YEAR)
  ) %>%
  group_by(STATE_NAME, YEAR) %>%
  summarize(
    total_projects = n(),
    successful_projects = sum(success_flag, na.rm = TRUE),
    success_rate = successful_projects / total_projects,
    .groups = "drop"
  )

ks_us_state_year %>%
  arrange(STATE_NAME, YEAR) %>%
  head(20) %>%
  kbl(
    digits = 3,
    caption = "Sample of U.S. StateâYear Kickstarter Panel"
  ) %>%
  kable_styling(full_width = FALSE)

```


## Results

To link Kickstarter outcomes to local economic conditions, I construct stateâyear measures of total employment using the CES dataset. For each stateâindustry pair, the CES data provide monthly employment levels, which I average to obtain annual employment. Summing across industries within each stateâyear gives a measure of the overall size of the labor market:

$$
\text{emp\_total}_{s,t} = \sum_k \text{employment}_{s,k,t},
\qquad
\text{Emp}_{s,t} = \log(\text{emp\_total}_{s,t}).
$$

These log employment levels form the endogenous variable in the instrumental variables strategy.

A key ingredient of the Bartik instrument is a set of **fixed exposure weights**, capturing the long-run industrial composition of each state. I compute these weights using average employment shares from the pre-period 2010â2012:

$$
\text{share}^{\text{base}}_{s,k}
=
\frac{\overline{\text{employment}}_{s,k,2010â2012}}
     {\sum_j \overline{\text{employment}}_{s,j,2010â2012}}.
$$

These baseline shares vary across states but are constant over time. They reflect each stateâs historical specialization across industries and are used to scale national industry shocks when constructing the Bartik instrument in the next subsection.

To validate these weights, I check that shares sum to one within each state and that all states have complete industry coverage. The resulting dataset provides both (i) annual total employment by state and (ii) fixed state, industry exposure weights, both of which are necessary for building the shiftâshare instrument.


```{r emp-state-year-and-shares}

state_emp <- df_yearly %>%
  group_by(state_name, Year) %>%
  summarize(
    emp_total = sum(value, na.rm = TRUE),
    .groups = "drop"
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    log_emp_total = log(emp_total)
  )

# Baseline industry shares using early years (2010â2012)
baseline_shares <- df_yearly %>%
  filter(Year %in% 2010:2012) %>%
  group_by(state_name, industry) %>%
  summarize(
    emp_baseline = mean(value, na.rm = TRUE),
    .groups = "drop"
  ) %>%
  group_by(state_name) %>%
  mutate(
    share = emp_baseline / sum(emp_baseline, na.rm = TRUE)
  ) %>%
  ungroup()

baseline_shares_check <- baseline_shares %>%
  group_by(state_name) %>%
  summarize(
    share_sum = sum(share, na.rm = TRUE),
    n_industries = n(),
    .groups = "drop"
  )

baseline_shares_check %>%
  head(10) %>%
  kbl(
    digits = 3,
    caption = "Baseline Industry Shares: Sum of Shares by State (Check)"
  ) %>%
  kable_styling(full_width = FALSE)

```

#### 1: National Industry Shocks and Bartik Instrument

The Bartik instrument combines fixed stateâindustry exposure weights with national industry employment shocks. Using the CES data, I first compute national employment for each industry and year and construct annual macroeconomic shocks as year-on-year log changes:

$$
g_{k,t} = \Delta \log(\text{national employment in industry } k).
$$

These shocks capture national demand or technological trends that shift employment in each industry in ways unrelated to individual states.

The Bartik instrument for state $s$ in year $t$ is then constructed as a weighted average of these shocks, using the fixed baseline stateâindustry shares from 2010â2012:

$$
B_{s,t}
=
\sum_k \text{share}^{\text{base}}_{s,k} \cdot g_{k,t}.
$$

Because the exposure shares vary across states but are fixed over time, and the national shocks vary across years but are common across states, their interaction generates state-specific predicted changes in employment driven only by national industry trends. This provides plausibly exogenous variation for identifying the causal effect of local employment on Kickstarter outcomes.

The resulting stateâyear series $B_{s,t}$ excludes the first year of data, as national shocks require lagged employment to compute year-over-year changes.


```{r bartik-construction}

# National industry employment and shocks
nat_industry <- df_yearly %>%
  group_by(industry, Year) %>%
  summarize(
    emp_nat = sum(value, na.rm = TRUE),
    .groups = "drop"
  ) %>%
  arrange(industry, Year) %>%
  group_by(industry) %>%
  mutate(
    g_shock = log(emp_nat) - log(lag(emp_nat))   # Î log national employment
  ) %>%
  ungroup()

# Stateâyear Bartik instrument: sum_k share_{s,k} * g_shock_{k,t}
bartik_panel <- baseline_shares %>%
  select(state_name, industry, share) %>%
  left_join(nat_industry, by = "industry") %>%
  group_by(state_name, Year) %>%
  summarize(
    bartik_iv = sum(share * g_shock, na.rm = TRUE),
    .groups = "drop"
  ) %>%
  filter(!is.na(bartik_iv))   # drop first year with missing shocks

# Quick check
bartik_panel %>%
  arrange(state_name, Year) %>%
  head(20) %>%
  kbl(
    digits = 4,
    caption = "Sample of Bartik Instrument by State and Year"
  ) %>%
  kable_styling(full_width = FALSE)

```

#### 2: Merging Kickstarter and Employment Panels

We now merge:

* The Kickstarter stateâyear panel (`ks_us_state_year`),
* The stateâyear employment totals (`state_emp`), and
* The Bartik instrument (`bartik_panel`).

To keep a common support, we restrict to overlapping years between Kickstarter and CES (2010â2023).

```{r merge-panels}

ks_us_state_year_trim <- ks_us_state_year %>%
  filter(YEAR >= 2010, YEAR <= 2023)

# Merge
panel <- ks_us_state_year_trim %>%
  left_join(
    state_emp,
    by = c("STATE_NAME" = "state_name",
           "YEAR"       = "Year")
  ) %>%
  left_join(
    bartik_panel,
    by = c("STATE_NAME" = "state_name",
           "YEAR"       = "Year")
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    log_total_projects = log(total_projects)
  ) %>%
  filter(
    !is.na(log_emp_total),
    !is.na(bartik_iv)
  )

# Inspect merged panel
panel %>%
  select(STATE_NAME, YEAR,
         total_projects, success_rate,
         log_emp_total, bartik_iv) %>%
  arrange(STATE_NAME, YEAR) %>%
  head(20) %>%
  kbl(
    digits = 3,
    caption = "Merged StateâYear Panel (Kickstarter Ã Employment Ã Bartik)"
  ) %>%
  kable_styling(full_width = FALSE)

```

#### 3: OLS and Instrumental Variables Estimates

In the final step, I estimate the relationship between stateâyear Kickstarter performance and local labor-market conditions. The outcome variable is the success rate of projects launched in each stateâyear cell. The key regressor is the log of total state employment, which is potentially endogenous due to omitted economic conditions that may jointly influence employment and crowdfunding activity.

I first estimate a fixed-effects OLS model of the form:

$$
\text{success\_rate}_{s,t}
= \beta_{\text{OLS}}\;\text{Emp}_{s,t}
  + \gamma\,\log(\text{projects}_{s,t})
  + \eta_s + \tau_t + \varepsilon_{s,t},
$$

where $\eta_s$ and $\tau_t$ capture all time-invariant state characteristics and nationwide year shocks.

To address the endogeneity of employment, I then use the Bartik instrument constructed earlier to obtain a consistent 2SLS estimate:

$$
\text{success\_rate}_{s,t}
= \beta_{\text{IV}}\;\widehat{\text{Emp}}_{s,t}
  + \gamma\,\log(\text{projects}_{s,t})
  + \eta_s + \tau_t + u_{s,t},
$$

with the first stage:

$$
\text{Emp}_{s,t}
= \lambda B_{s,t} + \eta_s + \tau_t + \nu_{s,t}.
$$

The IV specification therefore identifies the effect of predicted employment growth driven by national industry trends interacting with fixed state-level industry composition. The coefficient $\beta_{\text{IV}}$ represents the causal effect of employment on crowdfunding success under the exclusion restriction.


```{r iv-estimation}

library(fixest)
library(modelsummary)

# OLS with state and year fixed effects
ols_model <- feols(
  success_rate ~ log_emp_total + log_total_projects | STATE_NAME + YEAR,
  data = panel
)

# IV model: log_emp_total instrumented by bartik
iv_model <- feols(
  success_rate ~ log_total_projects | STATE_NAME + YEAR |
    log_emp_total ~ bartik_iv,
  data = panel
)

# Compare results
modelsummary(
  list(
    "OLS"        = ols_model,
    "IV (BARTIK)" = iv_model
  ),
  coef_map = c(
    "log_emp_total"      = "Log Employment",
    "log_total_projects" = "Log Total Projects",
    "fit_log_emp_total"  = "Fitted Log Employment"
  ),
  stars = TRUE,
  statistic = "({std.error})",
  gof_omit = "AIC|BIC|Log.Lik|F|RMSE|Std.Errors"
)

```


## Conclusion

The OLS results show no evidence of a relationship between log employment and Kickstarter success rates at the stateâyear level. The estimated coefficient is close to zero (0.007) and statistically insignificant. This suggests that, in simple fixed-effects regressions, variation in state employment levels does not meaningfully predict crowdfunding success after accounting for differences in project volume and unobserved state and year effects.

The IV estimates using the Bartik shiftâshare instrument also produce an imprecise coefficient on log employment. The point estimate is larger (0.212) but remains far from statistically significant, and the associated standard error is substantial (0.648). This pattern indicates a weak first stage: the Bartik instrument does not strongly predict state-level employment within this sample, making it challenging to obtain a precise causal estimate.
